			  <table border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		        <tr>
		          <td><h3>What Types of Certification are Available?</h3></td>
		        </tr>
		      </table>
			  <table border="0" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		        <tr>
		           <td class="RegText">
					    <img border="0" src="/images/IPREAlogo.gif" width="150" height="58" align="right">
                        
                        <p> There are three levels of
                        professional certification based on
                        different levels of education and
                        experience:</p>
						
                        <ul>
                            <li>Certified Park &amp; Recreation
                                Professional (CPRP)</li>
                            <li>Provisional Park &amp; Recreation
                                Professional (PPRP)</li>
                            <li>Associate Park &amp; Recreation
                                Professional (APRP)</li>
                        </ul>
						
                        <p><h4>Certified Park and Recreation
                        Professional (CPRP)</h4>
                        A Bachelor's Degree from an NRPA/AALR
                        accredited program, verified by official
                        transcript, and pass the CPRP
                        examination.</p>
						
                        <p><strong>OR</strong></p>
						
                        <p>A Bachelor's Degree or higher from a
                        regionally accredited education
                        institution (without NRPA/AALR
                        accreditation), verified by official
                        transcript, with a major in recreation,
                        park resources and leisure services, and
                        no less than two years full-time
                        experience (following the degree) in a
                        recreation, park resources and leisure
                        service position, and pass the CPRP
                        examination.</p>
						
                         <p><strong>OR</strong></p>
                        <p>A Bachelor's Degree or higher from a
                        regionally accredited educational
                        institution, verified by official
                        transcript, with a major other than
                        recreation, park resources and leisure
                        services, and no less than five years
                        full-time experience (following the
                        degree) in a recreation, park resources
                        and leisure service position, and pass the CPRP
                        examination.</p>
						
                        <p>The final qualification for attaining
                        CPRP status is successful completion of
                        the national examination.</p>
						
                        <p><h4>Provisional Park &amp; Recreation
                        Professional (PPRP)</h4>
                        Provisional Park and Recreation Professional is a 
                        temporary classification for the following:</p>
						<ul>  
                         <li>eligible applicants waiting to sit for 
                             the national examination,</li>
                         <li>applicants with a major in recreation/park 
                             resources but lacking experience,</li>
                         <li>applicants with a major other than 
                             recreation/ park resources and no less than three years 
                             related experience following the degree.</li>
						</ul>
                        <p><h4>Associate Park &amp; Recreation
                        Professional (APRP)</h4>
                        An Associate's Degree (two-year) from a
                        regionally accredited institution,
                        verified by official transcript, with a
                        major in recreation, park resources and
                        leisure services.</p>
                           
						<p><strong>OR</strong></p>
                        
						<p>An Associate's Degree from a
                        regionally accredited educational
                        institution, verified by official
                        transcript with a major other than
                        recreation, park resources and leisure
                        services, and no less than two years
                        full-time experience (following the
                        degree) in a recreation, park resources
                        and leisure service position.</p>
						
                        <p><strong>OR</strong></p>
                        
						<p>A High School Diploma or equivalency
                        certificate, verified by official
                        documentation and no less than four years
                        full-time experience (following the
                        diploma or certificate) in a recreation,
                        park resources and leisure service
                        position.</p>
						
                        <p>
						  <em><strong>Note:</strong>
                        There is no examination requirement for APRP status.</em></p>
